com.projetloki.genesis

Class PseudoClass

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.projetloki.genesis.PseudoClass

  • public final class PseudoClass
extends Object
    A pseudo-class specifies a special state of the element to be selected. For example :hover will apply a style when the user hovers over the element specified by the selector.

      • ACTIVE

        public static final PseudoClass ACTIVE
        Matches when an element is being activated by the user. It allows the page to give a feedback that the activation has been detected by the browser. When interacting with a mouse, this is typically the time between the user presses the mouse button and releases it. It is often used on <a> and <button> HTML elements.

        MDN

      • ENABLED

        @PoorBrowserSupport
public static final PseudoClass ENABLED
        Represents any enabled element. An element is enabled if it can be activated (e.g. selected, clicked on or accept text input) or accept focus. The element also has an disabled state, in which it can't be activated or accept focus.
        See Also:
        MDN, Browser support

      • DISABLED

        @PoorBrowserSupport
public static final PseudoClass DISABLED
        Represents any disabled element. An element is disabled if it can't be activated (e.g. selected, clicked on or accept text input) or accept focus. The element also has an enabled state, in which it can be activated or accept focus.
        See Also:
        MDN, Browser support

      • CHECKED

        @PoorBrowserSupport
public static final PseudoClass CHECKED
        Represents any radio (<input type="radio">), checkbox (<input type="checkbox">) or option (<option> in a <select>) element that is checked or toggled to an on state. The user can change this state by clicking on the element, or selecting a different value, in which case the :checked pseudo-class no longer applies to this element, but will to the relevant one.
        See Also:
        MDN, Browser support

    • Method Detail

      • lang

        public static PseudoClass lang(Locale lang)
        Returns a pseudo-class that matches elements based on the language the element is determined to be in. In HTML, the language is determined by a combination of the lang attribute, the <meta> element, and possibly by information from the protocol (such as HTTP headers). There is a match if the language code of the element starts with lang followed by a hyphen.

        For example, if lang is Locale.FRENCH, the pseudo-class will match elements whose language specification is fr, fr-CA, fr-FR, and so on.

        See Also:
        MDN

      • not

        public static PseudoClass not(Selector simpleSelector)
        Returns a pseudo-class that matches elements that are not matched by the given simple selector. Simple selectors are:
        • the universal selector
        • ID selectors
        • class selectors
        • attribute selectors
        • pseudo-class selectors
        Pseudo-element selectors are NOT simple selectors.

        Additionally, the given simple selector can't be the negation pseudo-class itself.

        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if the given selector is not a simple selector, or the given selector is the negation pseudo-class itself
        See Also:
        MDN
